    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "The analogy is a bit confusing. I'm not looking for a fairy tale, I just need to know if I'm personally liable for legal fees if the client gets sued because of something I did. Does this clause mean I have to pay for their lawyers out of my own pocket? Could you explain that part more clearly without the metaphors?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. Let's break it down without the goblin flair. This indemnification clause means that if you, as the freelancer, breach the contract or fail to fulfill your promises, you are responsible for covering any legal costs, damages, and other expenses that the Disclosing Party incurs as a result. This includes their attorney's fees. In essence, if the client decides to take legal action against you because of your breach or non-fulfillment, you would be liable for all associated legal costs, including their lawyers' fees. It's a way to ensure that the Disclosing Party is not left to bear the financial burden of any legal issues that arise from your actions or inactions. So, yes, this clause could mean you have to pay for their lawyers out of your own pocket if they get sued because of something you did. It's important to carefully consider this before signing the contract, as it places a significant financial responsibility on you.",
      "source": "target",
